        "We acknowledge that unique circumstances, including new large load additions seeking to come online more rapidly than generation may adequately support and extremely delayed generation queue study times, is driving the proposed ER\n[...]\nprocess. However, as\n[...]\n, Wisconsin has unaddressed concerns regarding the proposals disconnect between stated need and generator online dates as\n[...]\nas the effect of the current ERAS\n[...]\ncould have on regulatory\n[...]\nMISO adopted some of OMS’\n[...]\nRERRA acknowledgement language\n[...]\nWisconsin urges MISO\n[...]\nwritten, the section\n[...]\n9.1 redlines read, “…address a reliability and/or resource adequacy need identified by the RERRA\" instead\n[...]\n“resource should be considered for the ERAS process in order to meet a resource adequacy need that the state or LSE (or IC, where appropriate) has claimed.” MISO’s proposed language would\n[...]\nhave formally made its determination of need for a resource prior to approving its entrance into ERAS. While this may be the approach that some RERRAs take, the MISO proposal should avoid a requirement that states have either already made their determination of need or RERRAs could be guilty of pre-judging a project’s merit\n[...]\na resource adequacy need) before proper review\n[...]\nanalysis is conducted during the regulatory process. We are encouraged to hear that MISO is working with OMS to change this language back to OMS’s recommendation to address potential RERRA concerns.\n[...]\nEntergy encourages MISO to maintain the flexibility built into the RERRA acknowledgement but asks that MISO offer language that can assuage regulatory concerns on prejudging the outcome of projects that qualify for ERAS. For example, in its redlines, MISO could note in Attachment X, section 3.9.1 of the tariff that “Nothing in the RERRA acknowledgment shall prejudge the outcome of any RERRA-conducted regulatory proceeding.”"
