      "text": "Madison Pitts Associate Corporate Counsel Direct Dial: 317-316-7911 Email: mpitts@misoenergy.org\n\nJanuary 30, 2024\n\nVIA ELECTRONIC FILING\n\nDebbie-Anne Reese \nSecretary \nFederal Energy Regulatory Commission \n888 First Street, N.E \nWashington, D.C. 20246 \n\nRe: Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. Docket No. ER24-_____-000 Generator Replacement Improvement Revisions\n\nDear Secretary Reese:\n\nThe Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. (“MISO”) hereby submits 1proposed revisions to Attachment X—Generator Interconnection Procedures (“Attachment X”) and Module C—Energy and Operating Reserve Markets (“Module C”) of its Open Access Transmission Tariff (“Tariff”). The purpose of the revisions is to streamline MISO’s current generator replacement process and clarify certain other requirements. As part of these improvements, MISO proposes to align the study requirements found in its Attachment X with the requirements in Attachment Y Notification of Potential Resource (“Attachment Y”) for replacement requests, mitigate unnecessary study submission lead times for duplicative study requirements, and clarify the application of the one-year replacement submission requirement for facilities with an approved suspension request. These proposed revisions do not substantively change or expand the generator replacement process as accepted by the Commission. 2 MISO requests that the proposed revisions be made effective as of March 31, 2024, which is at least sixty (60) days after filing.\n\nI. BACKGROUND\n\nA. DEVELOPMENT OF THE GENERATOR REPLACEMENT PROCESS\n\nBefore the advent of generator replacement, owners of generating facilities had to use two separate procedures to convert an existing generating facility to a more efficient technology. First, the generator had to follow the procedure for the suspension or retirement of the existing generating facility under Section 38.2.7(a) of Module C and Attachment Y of the Tariff. This\n\n1 MISO makes this filing pursuant to section 205 of the Federal Power Act (“FPA”), 16 U.S.C. § 824d, and Part \n35 of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission’s (“FERC” or “Commission”) regulations, 18 C.F.R. § 35.0 \net seq. (2022). All capitalized terms in this filing that are not otherwise defined have the same meaning as they \nhave under the current MISO Tariff. \n2 Midcontinent Indep. Sys. Operator, Inc., 167 FERC ¶ 61,146 (“May 2019 Order”). \nSecretary Debbie-Anne Reese \nJanuary 30, 2024 \nPage 2 \n\n| process required the owner of the existing generating facility to submit a notice of the planned | | |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| retirement to MISO at least 26 weeks prior to the resource's retirement effective date (“Attachment | | |\n| Y Notice”). | During the Attachment Y Notice period, MISO would conduct a study to determine | |\n| whether all or a portion of the resource's capacity is necessary to maintain system reliability. | | If |\n| the resource’s capacity was necessary, it was designated as a | | System Support Resource (“SSR |\n| Unit”). If MISO could not maintain system reliability prior to the retirement effective date, then | | |\n| MISO required the SSR Unit to continue to operate, as needed, and MISO would compensate the | | |\n| resource owner accordingly. After the resource owner completed this process, the resource owner | | |\n| then had to submit a new interconnection request to MISO for the generating facility that would | | |\n| replace the existing generating facility. | | The replacement generating facility would be required to |\n| follow the full set of interconnection procedures under Attachment X in MISO's Tariff, which | | |\n| includes the Definitive Planning Phase (“DPP”). | | 6 Under this regime, the resource owner had no |\n| guarantee that it could retire the existing generating facility at the time proposed in the Attachment | | |\n| Y Notice. | This “dual track” retire and then replace process created numerous inefficiencies for | |\n| both MISO and Interconnection Customers, added costs, delay, and uncertainty to the process of | | |\n| replacing existing generation with new units. | | |\n| | | |\n| In 2012, MISO began revising | | its generator replacement process. 3 Specifically, MISO |\n| proposed to allow an owner or operator of a generating facility to retain its interconnection rights | | |\n| in certain circumstances after the submittal of the Attachment Y Notice and before retirement or | | |\n| termination of an SSR Agreement. | | 4 Similarly, MISO proposed to allow an owner or operator to |\n| modify its decision to suspend a generation resource. | | 5 The Commission raised several concerns |\n| with MISO’s proposal, and, after two compliance | | filings, the Commission continued to have |\n| concerns with its proposal | | to allow the retention and transfer of interconnection service to another |\n| generator. | 6 The Commission ultimately rejected MISO’s proposal without prejudice. | 7 |\n| | | |\n| In 2019, MISO filed a detailed generator replacement process to address the Commission’s | | |\n| concerns and to facilitate the modernization of the generating fleet in the Midwest through a clear | | |\n| and robust process. | 8 The Commission accepted MISO’s proposal because it adequately addressed | |\n\nthe Commission concerns. 9 The Commission found, consistent with MISO’s goals, that the proposal “would prevent generating facility owners seeking to make infrastructure investments\n\n3 Midwest Indep. Sys. Operator, Inc., 140 FERC ¶ 61,237 (2012).\n\n4 Id., Transmittal Letter at 10\n\n5 Id.\n\n6 Midwest Indep. Transmission Sys. Operator, Inc., 153 FERC ¶ 61,313 (2015).\n\n7 Midwest Indep. Transmission Sys. Operator, Inc., 155 FERC ¶ 61,274 (2016).\n\n8 The 2019 proposals addressed concerns raised by the Commission with these previous efforts. Midcontinent Indep. Sys. Operator, Inc., 167 FERC ¶ 61,146 (2019).\n\n9 Id. at 23-24.\n\nfrom losing their existing interconnection service and potentially incurring significant costs to obtain replacement interconnection service at the same location.” 10 In making its decision, the Commission highlighted the inefficiency of requiring interconnection customers that intend replace an existing generating facility with type and level of service with no material adverse impact to the transmission system to go back through the queue and how creating efficiencies may eventually be reflected in lower rates for ratepayers. 11 The generator replacement process has been an invaluable tool to Interconnection Customers in MISO since 2019.\n\nB. MISO’S GENERATOR REPLACEMENT PROCESS\n\nThe generator replacement process approved in 2019 is largely 12 the same process used by MISO today. First, an interconnection customer must submit an interconnection request for replacement at least one (1) year before the Existing Generating Facility ceases operation. The replacement request must meet certain technical criteria concerning the location of the Point of Interconnection, the level of service (i.e. ERIS or NRIS), and the amount of MW. 13 Replacement requests may be modified at any time before the evaluation process is complete. 14 MISO evaluates replacement requests in the order received and will complete both a Replacement Impact Study (“RIS”) and a Reliability Assessment Study (“RAS”). 15 The RIS determines whether the request will have a material adverse impact on the MISO transmission system, which is the same standard used to determine whether a change is a material modification. 16 The RAS, in contrast, compares the conditions of the transmission system as they exist with the Existing Generating Facility online with those that would exist if the existing generating facility is taken offline for a period not to exceed three (3) years. 17 If the RAS identifies reliability impacts, MISO will require the interconnection customer seeking replacement to mitigate any reliability violation before its\n\n10 Id. at 31.\n\n11 Id.\n\n12 Midcontinent Indep. Sys. Operator, Inc., 177 FERC ¶ 61,020 (2021) (Order accepting MISO’s prop",
